I know Christmas hasn’t even gotten here yet, but I LOVE planning out my goals in advance. Here’s 3 questions to think about to help make sure you’re choosing goals you actually want for next year:

1️⃣ Are you being genuine? 
Think about whether you actually want a specific goal, or whether you feel like you *should* because you see everyone else on Instagram posting reels about ‘eating healthy’ or reading X amount of books. Is it actually something you want to create time & attention for in your life?

2️⃣ Do I have control of it happening? Make sure the result is something you actually have control of. Ex: If you want to find your future spouse in 2023, you can do things to create opportunities to meet people or make sure you’re emotionally prepped- but you can’t control the actions of another person, so maybe change the focus of the goal to be something that IS in your control instead. Like, downloading a dating app, going to therapy, signing up for a group class/activity, etc. 

3️⃣ Does it need to be a year-long goal? This can be viewed in two ways: 1) If your goal is to travel more in 2023, maybe you can focus it on visiting one new place each month. 2) Is it a goal or an intention? A goal is something that has a specific accomplishment, but an intention leads more of a lifestyle change. 

Let me know what other questions are good things to think about when goal-setting for the new year!

First time skijoring with Leo & I’m already in love 😍🎿🐺

Ever since I got a husky, this has been the goal. I on purpose didn’t get a ski pass this year, and now I can’t wait to get better at it so we can go on some harder runs. 

We rented cross country skis & headed up to Park City to some free spots that are good for beginners & dog-friendly. I’ve had the pulling harnesses and tug line for a while now and we’ve done training using them to work up to this. The hardest part was his excitement to sprint in the beginning that got him tired quicker than I thought. I’ve heard there’s spots closer to us, so I can’t wait to keep training him & improving together. 

If anyone has any skijoring tips, those are always appreciated! 🥰

When I was 16, I remember working at my family’s martial arts studio booth at a local festival. Some parents walked up and asked for info about classes for their son. I started talking to them and noticed their younger daughter excitedly going up and trying to break a board with her brother, so I asked if they wanted a class for her as well. They instantly laughed and said, “No, she’s a girl- she’s too sweet. She’s made for things like dance and ballet.”

I never saw that family again, but what I want to say to every parent who thinks their daughters wouldn’t excel in martial arts cause it’s a ‘boy sport’:
I started off as a shy & nervous 5yr old girl that was scared of people speaking loudly to me, somehow I ended up traveling all of the world to kick people & my favorite thing is speaking in public. And to every girl who never got the opportunity to learn martial arts growing up- there’s always now! 🤗

#Taekwondo #BlackBelt #FemaleMartialArtist

My senior year at UVU included most of my free time spent working out in the gym at the SLWC. I had one final goal of making it on the US Collegiate National Taekwondo Team just one more time after a year spent recovering from my ankle ligament surgery. Balancing between midterms, my capstone project, and twice a day training sessions felt a little insane- but I was determined. 

As the end of the semester approached, so did Collegiate Nationals. I would have to fight to win every match against top schools all over the country. My least favorite part of all this was not being able to have fun snacks while studying for finals so I could stay in my fighting weight class 😂

I flew over to DC for Nationals, and all of the sudden it was fight day🔥 I had a tough bracket and after an entire day of fights I made it to finals. I was bruised, sore and exhausted, but as I walked on the mat I thought back to exactly one year ago when I had lost my first match & gone home to a surgery to fix my 2 torn ligaments. On that plane ride home I had committed to do everything I could to make it back here to this moment- so I went out and had the best fight of my life 🥇

I flew home & graduated with my Marketing bachelors degree from UVU. This was also I goal I hadn’t wanted to give up on even though at times I envied other athletes that could just train all day. Looking back now, it was all worth it 💪🏻💚🤍 #DiscoverUVU #Sponsored

Advice for new graduates! 👩🏻‍🎓 It’s graduation time & here’s a few of the things I wish I knew looking back when I graduated from @utah.valley.university 4 years ago! 💚 #DiscoverUVU #Sponsored 

1. Have a plan but be open to change. You might think you know exactly what you want to be now that you’ve “grown up” but life likes to throw curveballs and that’s ok, embrace the changes that feel right to you.

2. Don’t compare yourself to others. You might look at old classmates who graduated with you and they may be getting married, having kids, buying houses, starting a business, traveling– or who knows what else. The point is, everyone is on a different path and it always looks easier from the outside. 

3. Networking can be magic. You might not feel like you’re great at it, and it might take practice- but go to events, introduce yourself, and make those connections. If you graduated from UVU, make sure to connect with the UVU Alumni program, you already have something in common to talk about!

4. Learn how to budget - Once you get your first job, you might be tempted to spend your first paycheck on things you don’t actually need. Make a plan on what you want to be consciously spending your money on. 

5. Get comfortable spending time alone. This one is important so you don’t make choices based on what everyone else is doing. Once you graduate, you might feel like you lose your sense of community- but learn how to be your own best friend so you can learn more about yourself & what you want to spend time on.

6. Dream jobs take time - Your career is more than just the first job you take. Learn as much as you can & find good mentors to help you get there.

A couple of months ago I got the idea that I wanted to have a Husky 5K Run for my birthday. I had no idea how I was going to make this happen, but there’s not a lot of races you can do with your dog & it seemed like the perfect combination to get a bunch of dogs out and getting exercised, and help fundraise to help huskies! 

Fast forward to this past weekend, and I was completely blown away by the amount of people who came out to support 🤗 We had the BEST turnout at the event and had over 100 people come out to Wheeler Farm with their dogs, were able to raise $5,000 to help save more huskies, AND we found some new homes for some of our rescue dogs!! 💙

A huge thanks to Maren, our @arcticrescue director for trusting me to make this event happen & our amazing AR event planner volunteer, Nicole, for jumping right in and making it all come together even though she’s never been to an 5K before 😂 Also to every AR volunteer for being such an awesome group of women and putting so much time into caring about these dogs! And lastly, thank you to everyone who came out to the event, and those who signed up for the virtual 5K (I want to see your photos), all the foster fams, and adopters- thank you ✨🥰

Maybe this won’t be the year I run a half-marathon or hike Timp, but it’ll definitely be the year I prioritize getting healthy 💪🏻

Last summer, I was diagnosed with Graves’ Disease, an autoimmune disorder that causes hyperthyroidism. I found this out after I continued to push myself through workouts, but kept feeling worse each time. I lost so much weight that I was below my fighting weight back when I had competed. And I was constantly irritable and nervous, sweating every night and being way confused about what was going on with my body.

I haven’t enjoyed talking about this on IG, mostly cause I don’t want to be told ‘I’m sorry’s’. I hate feeling weak. 

However, I’ve had people reach out who also are going through their own Graves’ disease journeys that have questions & want to learn from my personal journey with it so far. If I can help by sharing, that’s what I want to be doing.

I started this IG to do that through my competitive journey in taekwondo. So it only makes sense to include the other life challenges & wins as well. 

#GravesDisease #autoimmunedisease #utah #huskymom #hyperthyroidism

My new happy song 🎵🤗
Here’s the update:
I’m not even sure I should be this happy, but it’s progress so I’ll take it. I had another blood work test this week & my TSH levels have gone from super super low (hyperthyroid) to the other range of too high (hypothyroid). 

What this essentially means is I’m taking too much medicine, so I’m going start decreasing the dosage and take another test in a couple of weeks to see if I can start weaning off!

Hypothyroid has its own set of issues, but I’m terribly optimistic I can level it out by reducing medicine and continuing my nutrition changes/GF diet & stress management 🤗

And second: my number of antibodies (the autoimmune issue) has decreased from +600 down to 177! A few months ago they were so high, they didn’t even give me an exact number 😂

Here’s to hoping I’m on my way to remission! ☀️

#gravesdisease #hyperthyroidism #utah #utahdogs #autoimmune #glutenfree

A week before I graduated back in 2018, I made a video on what I imagined my life would look like the first year after finally being done with school. I had fun goals on there like “try lobster” and “learn a backflip” along with some career goals like to be able to be a full-time YouTuber and win at USA Taekwondo Nationals. 

Between several changes to my major & spending most of my time traveling for competitions, it had taken me 9 years to slowly, but surely complete my bachelors degree. I was looking forward to finally being able to focus on my athletic career & social media goals without trying to also being a student. Which means the last thing I expected my next year to include was signing up for grad school & deciding to ‘retire’ from TKD competition 😂

This is a reminder to all new graduates to embrace the uncertainty, be open to change and unexpected opportunities. That first year was a tough one with long hours & tough decisions, but it went bigger than I could’ve expected. I’m so grateful for the things I learned during my time at @utah.valley.university to help set me up to achieving my big goals. And even though I still haven’t learned to backflip, I did create my dream job career as a video creator & earned a couple of play buttons 🤗

Guys! I might be able to stop taking medicine and be healthy soon 😍 

It’s been a crazy year and a half since I got diagnosed with Graves’ disease. I met with my endocrinologist this week and she was happy to see my levels are staying within normal ranges with only 1/3 of the medicine I started with. The next step is to double check my antibodies levels, but as long as that comes back within normal ranges, then we can try a month without meds and see if it’s gone into remission!

I’m pretty optimistic & even though it’ll be a rough adjustment while my body adapts for the first bit, but it would be so cool to feel “normal” again. Now I’ll be impatiently refreshing for my results all day tomorrow 😂

#gravesdisease #autoimmune #hyperthyroidism #functionalmedicine #naturopathic #glutenfree #utah

I got a late start to fall hiking this year, but still found three hikes I LOVED that are all about 20-30min from Draper! 

Rattlesnake Gulch Trail
📍 Millcreek Canyon
3.8 miles out & back
Off-leash on odd days, on-leash on even days

Three Falls Trail Loop
📍 Alpine, UT
Technically a 3.6mile loop, but we cheated and drove up to the falls area. The trailhead leads you to a parking lot, but only the second half of the trail has fall leaves. So, we drove up to the falls, walked the trail in reverse, then went to see the falls. 

Butterfield Canyon
📍Herriman, UT
They just created a whole new trailhead for this canyon and I honestly haven’t explored it much. I love that it’s not very crowded and there’s so many new places to explore. We only did a short hike here cause I had a foster husky with me, but it was still super pretty!

One of the things I want to share more of are close by places to go on quick adventures- not ones that take a whole weekend or day to do. Any others you’d suggest?

#utah #slc #utahfall #utahcounty #utahhiking #utahhikes #dogfriendlyslc

And after 16 months since first getting diagnosed with Graves’ disease… I’m finally off meds & have a healthy thyroid!! 🥳🙌🏻

I don’t think I ever valued my health as much as I’ve prioritized it this past 1.5years. When I think back to last summer, it was one of the worst seasons of my life. I had racing heart palpitations that woke me out of my sleep, lost so much weight, was anxious 24/7, and so many other symptoms I never want to experience again. 

Feeling “normal” felt like such a faraway goal, and I remember feeling so frustrated I couldn’t just go exercise all the stress out like I wanted. But slowly & with help from doctors, books, healthy habits, and encouraging people, I’m so happy to feel “normal” again. 

To celebrate I’m signing up for a 5K run and a tkd tournament in the next few months 🙌🏻 

While I’m still not technically in “remission” yet, I’m on my way! And though I may be destined to being gluten-free for the rest of my life, I’ll happily take that as a win. 🙏🏻

#gravesdisease #hyperthyroidism #healthy #functionalmedicine #autoimmune

How I ended up running a Husky Rescue 🩵🐾
Back in 2021, I saw these two huskies that had 2 days before they would be euthanized. Before I knew it, we would be bringing them home through @arcticrescue to save & foster them. 

I quickly fell in love with being able to help these creatures I cared so much about, but I also felt like I wanted to do more than just save one at a time. One thing led to another, and a year later I am grateful to be part of the leadership of such an amazing organization. 

While the videos show the highlight reel, there have been more challenges & sleepless nights than I could’ve imagined. Rescue is a crazy world that shows you both extremes of human selfishness & kindness. I’m so grateful for the AR Team we have that is creating so much positivity and make all these adventures worth it 🩵

I’ve never run a non-profit before, and we’re constantly trying to learn as much as we can while we grow. Now looking towards 2024, we have some crazy big goals ahead of us and I have zero doubts we’ll make it there! 🥳
